<br>
It's no secret: we are at a crossroads, a dangerous one at which resources have become limited, and the politics of the server loom over many aspects of our game play.  The length and reputed abuse of the Venril Sathir list that continues to frustrate players and guilds is just one obvious example.  Growth, and reservability are two others.  The frustrations of some larger guilds, justifiably and understandably, is yet another.  Solutions have been proposed, forum threads opened, all with mixed response, very polar response in fact, illustrating the gradual and inevitable pressure in the Brell Serilis pot.  More and more often we read, hear of, or even experience first-hand the results of this tension, and while we seek solutions together the pressure grows.  Our community, and the sense of respect and honor we have built, is at risk; people find their frustrations challenging, and in some cases surmounting, their desire to preserve the atmosphere of equality that has become tradition on our server.  Can a FCFS system work on our server?  I think so, honestly, yet although it is perhaps more efficient in terms of mobs killed over a given time - its strongest argument in my opinion - I fear for the impact it may have on our relationships with one another.  I'm not sure if all of us can maintain a sense of respect (not monopolizing, giving as well as taking, etc.).  Some posts I have read on our boards, and the boards of some guilds, make me uneasy.  But this is beyond the formal systems we may adopt together.<br>
<br>
My greatest concern here is for Brell, and we are making progress in this time of trial.  Too many people to name are attempting to forge a system that keeps the greater population in mind, and it isn't easy or without sacrifices.  Most importantly, beyond a philosophical difference between others and myself about what intentions mean - beyond the Plane of Growth, whether or not FCFS = FFA or not, etc - is the fact that the very spirit of our community is at stake.  I, for one, vote for honor and respect in whatever forms that may take.  I vote to preserve our respect for each other.   I vote to see justice come to those who abuse our system, whatever we decide and however that may be, even though I wish it wasn't necessary in the first place.  I vote for reason and understanding for everyone's opinion, in an attempt to seek a solution, with a desire for harmony foremost in our minds.<br>
<br>
For what it's worth, being only one player, I can promise you that I and those I hunt with will always honor your intentions: there are plenty of other things for us to do with our game time, and preserving the spirit of the server is more important to us than any equipment we may get.  <br>
<br>
It's all about being cool to each other.<br>
<br>
To emphasize what I personally, and many others for that matter, value most, I close with a paraphrased exchange that our Officer of Education, Nagasakee Waa, always has with young monks that we tutor periodically as part of our guild community service:<br>
<br>
Nagasakee says, &quot;I invite all of you to approach and inspect me, and tell me what the most valuable possession is I have.&quot;<br>
A half dozen monks inspect.<br>
Young monk 01 says, &quot;Hero Bracer.&quot;<br>
Young monk 01 says, &quot;I'm sorry, brother, I don't really know equipment very well.&quot;<br>
Young monk 03 says, &quot;Robe of the Lost Circle.&quot;<br>
Young monk 04 shrugs.<br>
Young monk 05 says, &quot;Treant Fists.&quot;<br>
Young monk 06 says, &quot;Cane of the Tranquil.&quot;<br>
Nagasakee says, &quot;My most valuable possession is my reputation.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
In deep solidarity and hope for our future,<br>
<br>
Jagriel Jubei<br>
Sensei of the Zan Fi Monks<br>
