 <B>Dynin Vifargent</B></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uganonstormwynd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ganon Stormwynd</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.angelfire.com/il/selectevil/icons/Icon_Fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/1/01 4:48:40 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.greyhawk.net/gano1.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Preserving the spirit of the server</span><hr size=1> An excellent post Jagriel.<br>
<br>
Politics have always existed on Brell.  To deny that, or to consider earlier attempts at dealing with it as unimportant, limit our view of how the server matured into what we have today. <br>
<br>
Reservations existed on Brell very early on.  While there is debate as to when people started reserving things, I think we can all agree that at some point people felt the need to schedule their raids due to competition.<br>
<br>
The spirit of this server has been evolving for a long time.  Who remembers the discussions we had about the rights of a guild to claim loot on a raid?  Who remembers the attacks on guilds who contemplated it?  Who now accepts and encourages it by turning their head?<br>
<br>
Who turns their head when a member of this community can steal from another member and still lead a raid supported by the community?  Who allows someone to camp out in a Plane, regardless if that person intends to help his brothers and sisters out in the other?<br>
<br>
When the leader of a guild instructs its members to not adventure with the members of another guild, despite any friendship, because someone's ego was stepped on... is that the spirit you speak of?<br>
<br>
I argue, Jagriel, that this server's spirit died long ago.  Too many people, all scrambling to satisfy their own needs as individuals.<br>
<br>
When it no longer matters who you have helped previously your confidence in the spirit declines.  When you go beyond what is considered fair to help others out and get flamed for it, the spirit begins to fade.  And when you realize, deep down inside, that no matter how much help you offer you'll always be viewed as the evil uberguild, you understand that the spirit you held so high before is nothing but a shadow of your own need for self-worth.<br>
<br>
I started a guild that welcomed joining other people on raids.  We encouraged joint-ventured events so that we could keep communications with other guilds and individuals on the server a priority.  We were small, and we felt that we could embrace this server's population with open arms.<br>
<br>
Then we saw the dark side of human nature.  Independent raiders, claiming loot that they couldn't possibly attain on their own, seen regularly.  Complaints from the community that we were a uberguild, and we cared nothing for anyone but ourselves despite everything we'd done for others.  Accusations that we wanted to controll everything, from reservations and message boards, to ubermobs and other guilds.<br>
<br>
You begin to realize why a guild which is capable of doing things on their own would start to question why they aren't.  You might understand a guild's apathy for the community they helped keep fair to everyone, when &quot;everyone&quot; doesn't seem to care what is fair for that guild.  And you might recognize why a guild no longer cares what happens to the community because the only reputation that seems to matter is the honor between that guild's members.<br>
<br>
I contend Jagriel, whom I once called my friend, that this server's spirit was dead before you put words to your emotions.  I appreciate your desire to see the server return to its previous glory.  I, too, once dreamed of seeing this server realize its roots of familiarity and consequences.  However; Given the large number of people who don't or can't honor those ideals, I feel it is no longer possible.<br>
<br>
